cribes the exodus is not the way it happened, if it happened at all.” This seeming challenge to the biblical story captivated the local public. Yet as the rabbi himself acknowledged, his sermon contained nothing new. The theories that he described had been common knowledge among biblical scholars for over thirty years, though few people outside of the profession know their relevance.New understandings concerning the Bible have not filtered down beyond specialists in university settings. There is a need to communicate this research to a wider public of students and educated readers outside of the academy. This volume seeks to meet this need, with accessible and engaging chapters describing how archeology, theology, ancient studies, literary studies, feminist studies, and other disciplines now understand the Bible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aRELIGION / Bible / General.2bisacsh  aAccessible.  aBible.  aancient.  aarcheology.  achapters.  adescribing.  adisciplines.  aengaging.  afeminist.  aliterary.  aother.  astudies.  atheology.  aunderstand.1 aBerlin, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloch-Smith, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenspahn, Frederick E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreenspoon, Leonard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMachinist, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRendsburg, Gary A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSweeney, Marvin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWestbrook, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g